summary:
US strikes destroyed a major highway bridge outside Tehran and a public health institution. The targets followed President Trump's threats during his address on Iran war progress. Iranian transport and services for millions face disruptions. Further strikes on power plants are possible as operations continue.

Defense Secretary Pete Hegseth requested early retirement for Army Chief of Staff Gen. Randy George amid the US war against Iran. Pentagon leadership changes affect military readiness; a successor search has begun. Separately, President Trump signed an executive order imposing up to 100% tariffs on select patented drugs from pharmaceutical companies without 'most favored nation' pricing deals. US drug buyers and global pharma firms face higher costs; negotiations are underway. The UN Security Council schedules a vote Friday on a Gulf-led resolution authorizing a defensive force to secure Strait of Hormuz shipping. Global energy trade remains at risk from Iranian actions; approval would enable naval deployments.

In Myanmar, junta leader Min Aung Hlaing won a parliamentary vote for presidency in the pro-military assembly, five years after the coup. The country's 50 million residents face continued military rule amid civil war. NATO launched its first coordinated response to a severed deep-sea cable in the Baltic Sea, suspected as sabotage. Alliance members are enhancing infrastructure defenses; investigations seek culprits. NASA's Artemis II crew of three Americans and one Canadian ignited engines for a lunar flyby trajectory, solar eclipse view, and distance records, with return expected in weeks. SpaceX's Crew-10 mission launched NASA astronauts Anne McClain and Nichole Ayers, Japan's Takuya Onishi, and Russia's Kirill Peskov to the ISS to retrieve Butch Wilmore and Suni Williams, stuck nine months. President Trump dismissed Attorney General Pam Bondi, whose tenure involved Epstein files; an acting AG serves pending confirmation. Human Rights Watch reported Burkina Faso security forces and militias caused most civilian deaths in the Sahel conflict, targeting Fulani more than militants."}
